description:
Hooks must be called at the top level of a component or custom hook, in the same order every render. Never call hooks inside conditionals, loops, or nested functions — React relies on call order to track state.

Bad:
```jsx
if (isLoggedIn) {
  const [name, setName] = useState('');
}
```

Good:
```jsx
const [name, setName] = useState('');
// use `name` conditionally in the render, not the hook itself
```

When two or more components share stateful logic, extract it into a custom hook. Custom hooks compose — they can call other hooks. Name them `use*` so React enforces hook rules.

Example:
```jsx
function useDebounce(value, delay) {
  const [debounced, setDebounced] = useState(value);
  useEffect(() => {
    const id = setTimeout(() => setDebounced(value), delay);
    return () => clearTimeout(id);
  }, [value, delay]);
  return debounced;
}

// Usage in any component
const debouncedSearch = useDebounce(query, 300);
```

Wrap major UI sections in error boundaries so a crash in one widget doesn't take down the entire page. Place them at route level, around third-party components, and around data-dependent sections.

```jsx
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = { hasError: false };
  static getDerivedStateFromError() { return { hasError: true }; }
  componentDidCatch(error, info) { logError(error, info); }
  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) return <FallbackUI onRetry={() => this.setState({ hasError: false })} />;
    return this.props.children;
  }
}

// Usage
<ErrorBoundary><Dashboard /></ErrorBoundary>
```

Error boundaries catch errors in rendering, lifecycle methods, and constructors — not in event handlers or async code.

List keys must be stable across renders, unique among siblings, and derived from the data — never from the array index (unless the list is truly static and never reordered).

Bad:
```jsx
{items.map((item, index) => <Item key={index} {...item} />)}
// Reordering or inserting corrupts component state
```

Bad:
```jsx
{items.map(item => <Item key={Math.random()} {...item} />)}
// Forces full remount every render
```

Good:
```jsx
{items.map(item => <Item key={item.id} {...item} />)}
```

Start with state in the component that uses it. Only lift state up when a sibling genuinely needs it. Global state managers are for truly global concerns (auth, theme, feature flags) — not for form inputs or toggle states.

Bad:
```jsx
// Redux store holds isDropdownOpen for a single component
const isOpen = useSelector(s => s.ui.headerDropdownOpen);
```

Good:
```jsx
// Local state — only this component cares
const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);
```

Rule of thumb: if only one component reads the state, it belongs in that component.

Never use `useEffect` to synchronize state that can be computed from other state or props. Compute it inline during render, or use `useMemo` if the computation is expensive.

Bad:
```jsx
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
useEffect(() => setCount(items.length), [items]);
```

Good:
```jsx
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
const count = items.length; // derived — no state needed
```

The anti-pattern causes an extra render cycle and can lead to visual tearing where the UI briefly shows stale derived values.

Use `useRef` for values that need to persist across renders but shouldn't cause re-renders when they change: timer IDs, previous values, DOM references, instance-level flags.

```jsx
function useInterval(callback, delay) {
  const savedCallback = useRef(callback);
  // Update ref on every render so the interval always calls latest callback
  useEffect(() => { savedCallback.current = callback; });
  useEffect(() => {
    const id = setInterval(() => savedCallback.current(), delay);
    return () => clearInterval(id);
  }, [delay]);
}
```

Anti-pattern: using `useState` for values the UI never reads — it causes unnecessary re-renders.

Use React Suspense to declaratively handle loading states for lazy-loaded components and data fetching (with supporting libraries). Place Suspense boundaries strategically — one per meaningful loading zone, not one per component.

```jsx
const Dashboard = React.lazy(() => import('./Dashboard'));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<DashboardSkeleton />}>
      <Dashboard />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

Nest Suspense boundaries for granular loading: a page-level boundary shows a full skeleton, while a widget-level boundary shows individual widget placeholders.

Use `handle*` for the function definition and `on*` for the prop name. This creates a clear contract: the parent says what event it cares about, the child says how it handles it.

```jsx
// Parent
function Form() {
  const handleSubmit = (data) => { /* ... */ };
  return <SearchField onSubmit={handleSubmit} />;
}

// Child
function SearchField({ onSubmit }) {
  const handleKeyDown = (e) => {
    if (e.key === 'Enter') onSubmit(e.target.value);
  };
  return <input onKeyDown={handleKeyDown} />;
}
```

Consistent naming makes it immediately clear which functions are event handlers during code review.

Don't use `useEffect` to respond to events. Effects are for synchronizing with external systems, not for reacting to user actions. If something should happen when a button is clicked, put it in the click handler.

Bad:
```jsx
const [submitted, setSubmitted] = useState(false);
useEffect(() => {
  if (submitted) { sendAnalytics(); navigate('/thanks'); }
}, [submitted]);
const handleSubmit = () => setSubmitted(true);
```

Good:
```jsx
const handleSubmit = () => {
  sendAnalytics();
  navigate('/thanks');
};
```

The effect version adds an unnecessary state variable, an extra render, and makes the flow harder to trace.

When fetching data in `useEffect`, always handle cleanup to avoid setting state on unmounted components and to cancel stale requests.

Bad:
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch(`/api/user/${id}`).then(r => r.json()).then(setUser);
}, [id]);
// Race condition: fast id changes cause stale responses to overwrite fresh ones
```

Good:
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController();
  fetch(`/api/user/${id}`, { signal: controller.signal })
    .then(r => r.json())
    .then(setUser)
    .catch(e => { if (e.name !== 'AbortError') throw e; });
  return () => controller.abort();
}, [id]);
```

Better yet, use a data-fetching library (TanStack Query, SWR) that handles caching, deduplication, and race conditions.
